<h4 class="review-title">I Came In Like An Arian<span class="upvotes"></span><span class="downvotes"></span></h4>
<a href="#review-9394"><time>01/02/15</time></a>
<span class="review-author">By Locke</span>
</header>
<div class="review-body-wrapper">
<div class="review-body">
<div class="rates">
<span>Overall Score</span>
<span class="review-overall-score score" score="10"><p>&#xf005;&#xf005;&#xf005;&#xf005;&#xf005;</p></span>
</div>
<div class="review-content"><p>I`ll make this a simple (Edit: Apparently not.) and straighforward review: I like it. (<br/>Yes, it might be &#8220;tedious&#8221; at times BUT that is a good thing! What real novel is not!?</p>
<p>Books are supposed to be a canvas of words and information that the author paints to transmit an image.</p>
<p>Taking the above statement or rather my opinion into consideration makes the following true: Details are key. I find your writing to be detailed, precise and concise.</p>
<p>Just the way I like my cup of tea.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>I`d like to add that I might have given you a tad bit higher rating than the story <em>currently</em>  deserves seeing as I am a grammar nazi and I do like my chapters Arian.</p>
<p>^No story is complete without an ending, open or not.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>PS: More chapters please, but do keep them pristine.</p>
<p>PSS: In Third Royal Reich we spell incest with &#8220;in&#8221; like insane. We arians aren`t all that good at pronouncing W, so we tend to not use it as often as many others seem to like. In other words: Keep it little sister/older sister/sister figure/sister-ish/attractive mother/ugly mother/familiar person free, please. There`s enough of that as is.</p>
</div>
 
